{
  "text": "In many pedestrian detection applications, the size and computational cost of models is constrained. We experiment with a small and light-weight model Mo-bileNet [CITATION_1] , which is designed for mobile and embedded vision applications, to investigate if the performance improvements hold true. Table 16 shows results on CityPersons [CITATION_2] using MobileNet [CITATION_3] as a backbone network architecture into our baseline. Intuitively, MobileNet [CITATION_4] performs worse than the HRNet [CITATION_5] . However, in the case of MobileNet [CITATION_6] as well, we see pre-training on CrowdHuman [CITATION_7] and fine-tuning on CityPersons [CITATION_8] improves the performance of the MobileNet [CITATION_9] . Subsequently, we pre-train (3rd row) MobileNet [CITATION_10] on Crowd-Human [CITATION_11] and ECP [CITATION_12] before fine-tuning on CityPersons [CITATION_13] . Improvement of nearly 1% of M R \u22122 can be observed. Furthermore, we replaced CrowdHuman [CITATION_14] with Wider Pedestrian [1] as the initial source of pre-training. Improvement over the baseline (1st row) can be observed (4th row). Importantly, in the last row of Table 16 , largest gain can be observed. This is consistent with our previous finding reported in Table 12 , Wider Pedestrian [1] is a better source of pre-training than CrowdHuman [CITATION_15] , since it has images of autonomous driving scenes as well making it more diverse than CrowdHuman [CITATION_16] . Interestingly, in the case of CrowdHuman [CITATION_17] and Wider Pedestrian [1], even with a light-weight architecture, our baseline outperformed state-of-the-art pedestrian detector CSP [CITATION_18] . In summary, even with a light weight back-bone architecture, by pre-training on diverse and dense datasets, MobileNet [CITATION_19] outperformed previous best performing method on CityPersons [CITATION_20] , i.e. CSP [CITATION_21] .",
